<methodology slug="ops-metrics-basics">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>growth-marketer</domain>
    <summary>Metrics system for solopreneurs: choose 5-10 actionable metrics, automate collection, set alerts, review daily/weekly/monthly. Includes MRR, ARR, churn, LTV, CAC, ARPU, NRR formulas.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>metrics</tag>
      <tag>operations</tag>
      <tag>saas</tag>
      <tag>analytics</tag>
      <tag>reporting</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Ops Metrics Basics</title>
    <summary>A practical metrics management system for solopreneurs and small teams: choose 5-10 actionable metrics, implement collection from existing data sources, set targets and alerts, and establish a review cadence (daily pulse, weekly review, monthly deep-dive). Includes all core SaaS metric formulas (MRR, ARR, churn, LTV, CAC, ARPU, net retention).</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Operating on gut feeling produces late signals. A minimal metrics stack with automated collection, green/yellow/red status, and a fixed review rhythm converts data into timely decisions without requiring a data team. The discipline is choosing fewer metrics, not more.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Early-stage product that has some paying users but no formal metrics system.</item>
        <item>Solo operator who needs to answer "how is business?" with real numbers on demand.</item>
        <item>Team misaligned on what constitutes good/bad performance for the current phase.</item>
        <item>Setting up Stripe → Sheets → Looker Studio pipeline for the first time.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-revenue product — no payment data means the core metrics are undefined.</item>
        <item>Enterprises with dedicated BI teams — this pattern targets lean operations, not warehouse-scale analytics.</item>
        <item>When you want deep behavioral analytics — use product analytics tools (Mixpanel, Amplitude) instead of this ops-level framework.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Metric Selection for Solopreneurs">
      <section name="Selection Rule">
        <rule>
          <statement>Track at most 10 metrics at any time; include exactly one north star metric, two to three leading indicators, and two to three lagging measures of financial health.</statement>
          <rationale>Tracking too many metrics produces analysis paralysis and dilutes ownership. Fewer metrics with clear owners and targets produce faster decisions and clearer accountability.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>Prefer actionable metrics (metrics you can change with a specific intervention) over vanity metrics (metrics that look good but don't inform decisions).</statement>
          <rationale>Vanity metrics (total sign-ups all-time, page views) feel good to track but provide no decision signal. Actionable metrics (CAC by channel this month, churn rate) point to specific interventions.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>
      <section name="Metric Categories">
        <p>Five categories: North Star (ultimate success measure — active users or revenue), Leading (predict future outcomes — sign-ups, trial starts), Lagging (measure past results — revenue, churn), Input (actions you control — emails sent, ad spend), Output (results you want — conversions, revenue).</p>
      </section>
      <section name="Essential Solopreneur Metrics">
        <p>Minimum viable set with review frequency: Revenue (daily), MRR/ARR (weekly), active paying customers (weekly), churn rate (monthly), CAC (monthly), LTV (monthly), profit margin (monthly), runway (monthly). Do not add metrics beyond this set until the business has a dedicated operator for each new metric.</p>
      </section>
    </section>
    <section name="Tracking Stack, Targets, Alerts, and Review Cadence">
      <section name="Lean Tracking Stack">
        <rule>
          <statement>Use the simplest stack that answers your questions: Stripe → Google Sheets → Looker Studio covers 80% of solopreneur needs before a data warehouse is justified.</statement>
          <rationale>Complex analytics stacks require maintenance overhead that consumes time that could be spent on the business. Looker Studio's Stripe connector provides MRR, churn, and cohort data without custom SQL.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <p>Stack options by scale: smallest — Stripe + Google Sheets + Looker Studio; mid — Stripe + PostHog free tier + Looker Studio; largest pre-warehouse — Stripe + Mixpanel/Amplitude + Metabase.</p>
      </section>
      <section name="Target Setting">
        <rule>
          <statement>Set targets with three-level status thresholds: green (within 10% of target), yellow (10-20% below target), red (more than 20% below target); review red metrics in the next daily check-in.</statement>
          <rationale>Binary pass/fail targets produce false urgency and panic. Three-level thresholds match response effort to deviation severity and prevent over-reaction to normal variance.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>
      <section name="Alert Triggers">
        <p>Configure alerts for four conditions: revenue drop greater than 20% week-over-week (investigate immediately), churn rate above threshold (review immediately), zero sales for 24+ hours (check payment system health), CAC above target (review ad spend).</p>
      </section>
      <section name="Review Cadence">
        <p>Four frequencies: Daily pulse check (2 minutes — revenue and zero-sales alert); weekly performance review (30 minutes — full metrics table, went-well, needs-attention, next-week actions); monthly deep analysis (2 hours — cohort trends, CAC/LTV reconciliation, churn diagnosis); quarterly strategy review (half day — target reset, OKR alignment).</p>
        <reference path="templates/weekly-review.md">Weekly review template with metrics table and action items</reference>
      </section>
    </section>
    <section name="Core SaaS Metric Formulas and Antipatterns">
      <section name="Metric Formulas">
        <p>MRR = sum of all monthly recurring revenue. ARR = MRR × 12. Churn rate = customers lost in period / customers at start of period. LTV = ARPU / churn rate (in months). CAC = total marketing spend / new customers acquired. LTV:CAC ratio = LTV / CAC (target above 3:1, healthy above 5:1). ARPU = total revenue / total active customers. Net revenue retention = (starting MRR + expansion MRR - churn MRR) / starting MRR (target above 100%).</p>
      </section>
      <section name="Antipatterns">
        <antipattern>
          <description>Tracking more than 10 metrics simultaneously.</description>
          <reason>Analysis paralysis: no metric gets the attention needed to drive decisions. Prune to a maximum of 10 with clear owners before adding new metrics.</reason>
        </antipattern>
        <antipattern>
          <description>No targets set for key metrics.</description>
          <reason>Without targets, green/yellow/red status is undefined. Metrics without targets produce data without accountability, which is equivalent to not measuring at all.</reason>
        </antipattern>
        <antipattern>
          <description>Stale data from manual reporting with no automation.</description>
          <reason>Stale data produces stale decisions. Revenue and churn alerts that fire 2 weeks late prevent no damage. Automate Stripe → Sheets refresh to at minimum daily cadence.</reason>
        </antipattern>
        <antipattern>
          <description>Complex dashboards that no one opens.</description>
          <reason>Dashboard complexity directly reduces usage frequency. A simple 8-row table that is reviewed daily beats a 50-widget dashboard that is never opened.</reason>
        </antipattern>
      </section>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/weekly-review.md" purpose="Weekly review template: metrics table, went-well, needs-attention, next-week actions"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
